Various operations can be performed on pointers.

**Null Pointer:**
```cpp
int* ptr = nullptr;  // Modern C++ (C++11+)
int* ptr2 = NULL;    // Old style
int* ptr3 = 0;       // Also valid

if (ptr != nullptr) {
  // Safe to use pointer
}
```

**Pointer Arithmetic:**
```cpp
int arr[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
int* ptr = arr;

ptr++;      // Move to next integer
ptr--;      // Move to previous integer
ptr + 2;    // Move two positions forward
```

**Pointers and Arrays:**
```cpp
int arr[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
int* ptr = arr;

cout << *ptr << endl;      // 10 (first element)
cout << *(ptr + 1) << endl; // 20 (second element)
cout << ptr[2] << endl;    // 30 (third element)
```

**Looping with Pointers:**
```cpp
int arr[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
int* ptr = arr;

for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
  cout << *(ptr + i) << " ";
}
```

References are aliases for existing variables.

**Declaring References:**
```cpp
int num = 42;
int& ref = num;  // ref is now an alias for num

cout << num << endl;  // 42
cout << ref << endl;  // 42

ref = 100;
cout << num << endl;  // 100 (num changed through ref)
```

**References vs Pointers:**
```cppn// Reference
int num = 42;
int& ref = num;
ref = 100;  // num becomes 100

// Pointer
int num = 42;
int* ptr = &num;
*ptr = 100; // num becomes 100
```

**Key Differences:**
- References must be initialized
- References cannot be reassigned
- References cannot be null
- References are safer than pointers

**References in Functions:**
```cppnvoid swap(int& a, int& b) {
  int temp = a;
  a = b;
  b = temp;
}

int main() {
  int x = 5, y = 10;
  swap(x, y);
  // x = 10, y = 5
  return 0;
}
```

Pointers can be passed to functions for various purposes.

**Pass by Pointer:**
```cppnvoid modifyValue(int* ptr) {
  *ptr = 100;
}

int main() {
  int num = 42;
  modifyValue(&num);
  cout << num << endl; // 100
  return 0;
}
```

**Returning Pointers:**
```cppnint* createArray(int size) {
  int* arr = new int[size]; // Dynamic allocation
  for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
    arr[i] = i * 10;
  }
  return arr;
}

int main() {
  int* myArray = createArray(5);
  // Use array...
  delete[] myArray; // Free memory
  return 0;
}
```

**Const Pointers:**
```cppnint num = 42;
const int* ptr1 = &num;  // Pointer to const int
int* const ptr2 = &num;   // Const pointer to int
const int* const ptr3 = &num; // Const pointer to const int

*ptr1 = 50;  // Error: cannot modify
ptr1 = &other; // OK: can change pointer

*ptr2 = 50;  // OK: can modify
ptr2 = &other; // Error: cannot change pointer
```

Allocate memory at runtime using new and delete operators.

**new Operator:**
```cppnint* ptr = new int;    // Allocate single integer
*ptr = 42;

delete ptr;            // Free memory
ptr = nullptr;        // Good practice
```

**Dynamic Arrays:**
```cppnint size = 5;
int* arr = new int[size];

for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
  arr[i] = i * 10;
}

delete[] arr;  // Free array memory
arr = nullptr;
```

**Memory Leak Example:**
```cppn// BAD: Memory leak
int* ptr = new int;
ptr = new int; // Lost previous allocation

// GOOD: Proper cleanup
int* ptr = new int;
delete ptr;
ptr = new int;
delete ptr;
ptr = nullptr;
```

**Best Practices:**
- Always delete memory allocated with new
- Set pointer to nullptr after delete
- Use smart pointers (unique_ptr, shared_ptr) in modern C++
